aa(lp137
VThere are two ways of thinking about this.
p138
aVI'll give you one of them.
p139
aVSo imagine \u2014 let's suppose we're doing it.
p140
aVOn this side \u2014 remember, you're excited about head-tail-tail;
p141
aVyou're excited about head-tail-head.
p142
aVWe start tossing a coin, and we get a head \u2014
p143
aVand you start sitting on the edge of your seat
p144
aVbecause something great and wonderful, or awesome, might be about to happen.
p145
aVThe next toss is a tail \u2014 you get really excited.
p146
aVThe champagne's on ice just next to you; you've got the glasses chilled to celebrate.
p147
aVYou're waiting with bated breath for the final toss.
p148
aVAnd if it comes down a head, that's great.
p149
aVYou're done, and you celebrate.
p150
aVIf it's a tail \u2014 well, rather disappointedly, you put the glasses away
p151
aVand put the champagne back.
p152
aVAnd you keep tossing, to wait for the next head, to get excited.
p153
aa(lp154
VOn this side, there's a different experience.
p155
aVIt's the same for the first two parts of the sequence.
p156
aVYou're a little bit excited with the first head \u2014
p157
aVyou get rather more excited with the next tail.
p158
aVThen you toss the coin.
p159
aVIf it's a tail, you crack open the champagne.
p160
aVIf it's a head you're disappointed,
p161
aVbut you're still a third of the way to your pattern again.
p162
aVAnd that's an informal way of presenting it \u2014 that's why there's a difference.
p163
aVAnother way of thinking about it \u2014
p164
aVif we tossed a coin eight million times,
p165
aVthen we'd expect a million head-tail-heads
p166
aVand a million head-tail-tails \u2014 but the head-tail-heads could occur in clumps.
p167
aVSo if you want to put a million things down amongst eight million positions
p168
aVand you can have some of them overlapping, the clumps will be further apart.
p169
aVIt's another way of getting the intuition.
