aa(lp171
VWhat's the point I want to make?
p172
aVIt's a very, very simple example, an easily stated question in probability,
p173
aVwhich every \u2014 you're in good company \u2014 everybody gets wrong.
p174
aVThis is my little diversion into my real passion, which is genetics.
p175
aVThere's a connection between head-tail-heads and head-tail-tails in genetics,
p176
aVand it's the following.
p177
aVWhen you toss a coin, you get a sequence of heads and tails.
p178
aVWhen you look at DNA, there's a sequence of not two things \u2014 heads and tails \u2014
p179
aVbut four letters \u2014 As, Gs, Cs and Ts.
p180
aVAnd there are little chemical scissors, called restriction enzymes
p181
aVwhich cut DNA whenever they see particular patterns.
p182
aVAnd they're an enormously useful tool in modern molecular biology.
p183
aVAnd instead of asking the question, "How long until I see a head-tail-head?" \u2014
p184
aVyou can ask, "How big will the chunks be when I use a restriction enzyme
p185
aVwhich cuts whenever it sees G-A-A-G, for example?
p186
aVHow long will those chunks be?"
p187
aa(lp188
VThat's a rather trivial connection between probability and genetics.
p189
aVThere's a much deeper connection, which I don't have time to go into
p190
aVand that is that modern genetics is a really exciting area of science.
p191
aVAnd we'll hear some talks later in the conference specifically about that.
p192
aVBut it turns out that unlocking the secrets in the information generated by modern
p193
aVexperimental technologies, a key part of that has to do with fairly sophisticated \u2014
p194
aVyou'll be relieved to know that I do something useful in my day job,
p195
aVrather more sophisticated than the head-tail-head story \u2014
p196
aVbut quite sophisticated computer modelings and mathematical modelings
p197
aVand modern statistical techniques.
p198
aVAnd I will give you two little snippets \u2014 two examples \u2014
p199
aVof projects we're involved in in my group in Oxford,
p200
aVboth of which I think are rather exciting.
p201
aVYou know about the Human Genome Project.
p202
aVThat was a project which aimed to read one copy of the human genome.
p203
aVThe natural thing to do after you've done that \u2014
p204
aVand that's what this project, the International HapMap Project,
p205
aVwhich is a collaboration between labs in five or six different countries.
p206
aVThink of the Human Genome Project as learning what we've got in common,
p207
aVand the HapMap Project is trying to understand
p208
aVwhere there are differences between different people.
