aa(lp210
VWhy do we care about that?
p211
aVWell, there are lots of reasons.
p212
aVThe most pressing one is that we want to understand how some differences
p213
aVmake some people susceptible to one disease \u2014 type-2 diabetes, for example \u2014
p214
aVand other differences make people more susceptible to heart disease,
p215
aVor stroke, or autism and so on.
p216
aVThat's one big project.
p217
aVThere's a second big project,
p218
aVrecently funded by the Wellcome Trust in this country,
p219
aVinvolving very large studies \u2014
p220
aVthousands of individuals, with each of eight different diseases,
p221
aVcommon diseases like type-1 and type-2 diabetes, and coronary heart disease,
p222
aVbipolar disease and so on \u2014 to try and understand the genetics.
p223
aVTo try and understand what it is about genetic differences that causes the diseases.
p224
aVWhy do we want to do that?
p225
aVBecause we understand very little about most human diseases.
p226
aVWe don't know what causes them.
p227
aVAnd if we can get in at the bottom and understand the genetics,
p228
aVwe'll have a window on the way the disease works,
p229
aVand a whole new way about thinking about disease therapies
p230
aVand preventative treatment and so on.
p231
aVSo that's, as I said, the little diversion on my main love.
